SYPHILIS AND GONOCOCCAL DISEASE - USA: (OREGON) INCREASED INCIDENCE
*******************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 20 Dec 2013
Source: Oregon Public Broadcasting (OPB), The Register Guard report [edited]
http://www.opb.org/news/article/spike-in-std-cases-a-concern-for-county/


Facing a 3-year surge in the sexually transmitted diseases of gonorrhea and syphilis, Lane County Public Health Officer Paul Luedtke is asking doctors -- and residents -- for vigilance and for fast action at the 1st symptom. By the end of November [2013], the confirmed gonorrhea count in the county this year reached 202, already up 60 percent from 2012's total and climbing. Syphilis is a much smaller number, with 23 cases so far this year, but the historic pattern in Lane County is 1 or 2 cases annually. The disease tracking system isn't perfect, Luedtke said, and the tendency is to under report and so under count. "We are certain the numbers are higher for each disease," he said.

"Occasionally, if you look over a 10-year period, we do have little outbreaks of sexually transmitted diseases. This one is lasting longer than we want, and it's significantly higher than we want, so it's concerning," he said.

Luedtke said 3 trends are to blame for the spike in sexually transmitted diseases locally: the economy, public health program cuts, and a declining use of condoms. During the great recession, unemployment in Lane County exceeded 14 percent. "When our unemployment rate ticked up above 10 percent, many more people did not have access to health care. They were putting off things. Some of these (sexually transmitted diseases), they smolder for a while. People say, 'Oh, maybe it's nothing.' Of course, people don't stop having sex, so it spreads."

The public health system shoulders a share of the blame, Luedtke said. For years, the county told Lane County residents: "Come on in if you don't have insurance. Come on in if you have a problem and want to remain anonymous," Luedtke said. "Because of budget cuts several years ago, we got rid of that -- and it's very clear to us through surveys that people didn't really know where to go." In recent months, Lane County restarted a one-day-a-week clinic to see patients with sexually transmitted diseases, Luedtke said, "because we realized we were part of the problem."

Luedtke urges no delay in seeking treatment -- regardless of ability to pay. Free care is available through Community Health Centers of Lane County, Volunteers in Medicine, and the White Bird Clinic, he said. "If you don't have insurance or you haven't signed up for Cover Oregon yet because the system isn't working, you can still be seen. It's important for the community to know that," he said.

Luedtke also has a message for Lane County physicians: Bone up on diagnosis and treatment of sexually transmitted diseases. "Not all providers are diagnosing syphilis, for example, as they should," he said. Syphilis, a bacterial infection, first shows itself with an ulcer on the genitals. "If you don't treat it, the bug keeps replicating in your body," Luedtke said. Next, the patient gets a full body rash. Some doctors are misdiagnosing that as a viral rash rather than recognizing the secondary expression of syphilis. "People aren't thinking syphilis because for years we didn't have much syphilis," he said. "We're not alone; the state has a lot more syphilis than we've had for a long time."

Gonorrhea, also a bacterial infection, first shows in men as burning with urination and penile discharge. Women are asymptomatic half the time or have vaginal discharge and pelvic pain. Some local doctors aren't up to speed with the dosage of antibiotic needed to knock out gonorrhea, Luedtke said. The recommended dose used to be 125 mg of ceftriaxone, but now it's 250 mg, due to increased resistance of the bacteria to the antibiotic. "We still have people giving 125," Luedtke said. "The patient gets a little better. It doesn't hurt to pee anymore. The patient doesn't have pus coming out of their penis, but it only knocks the infection down 70, 80, 90 percent. They keep having sex. They spread the bugs, and within a week or so after taking the antibiotics, it comes back because it wasn't killed."

[Byline: Diane Dietz]

