[The state of Oregon can be seen on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at http://healthmap.org/r/9BEV. Lane County, with a population of 351 715 in 2010 (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lane_County,_Oregon#Government), extends from the Pacific Ocean to the Cascade mountain range; it can be located on the map at http://geology.com/county-map/oregon.shtml. Eugene, with a population of 156 185, is the 2nd-largest city in the state (after Portland) and the county seat.

In the US in 2000, the number of cases and the incidence rate of primary and secondary syphilis (P&S), contagious stages of syphilis, were 5979 and 2.1, respectively, the lowest since reporting began in 1941 (http://www.cdc.gov/std/stats11/tables/1.htm). The number of cases and incidence rate of P&S syphilis then increased almost yearly to 13 970 and 4.5 per 100 000 in 2011 (http://www.cdc.gov/std/stats11/tables/1.htm). The male-to-female rate ratio for P&S syphilis rates rose from 1.5 in 2000 to 8.2 in 2011 and in recent years, young men who have sex with men (MSM) have accounted for an increasing number of syphilis cases in the United States; in 2011, 72 percent of P&S syphilis cases were among MSM (http://www.cdc.gov/std/stats11/syphilis.htm).

Most cases of P&S syphilis in Oregon in 2011 were reported from Multnomah County (http://www.cdc.gov/std/stats11/tables/32.htm), which is part of the Portland metropolitan area and, though smallest in area, is the state's most populous county (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multnomah_County,_Oregon). Among counties and independent cities of the US ranked by number of cases reported in 2011, Multnomah County ranked 43rd highest with 71 cases of P&S syphilis and an incidence rate of 9.7 cases per 100 000 (http://www.cdc.gov/std/stats11/tables/32.htm), while the whole state of Oregon reported 97 cases in that year. In Oregon in 2011, the rate of P&S syphilis among males was 5.1 per 100 000 population compared to the US male rate of 8.2 per 100 000, but was increasing steeply since 2008 (http://www.cdc.gov/std/Syphilis2011/Syphilis-2011-All-Profiles.pdf).

Reported increases in incidence of infectious syphilis among MSM have been characterized by high rates of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) co-infection, high-risk sexual behavior, use of drugs such as methamphetamines, use of Internet chat rooms to meet sex partners (http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5510a1.htm) and more recently use of smartphone applications like Grindr, a gay social networking site (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grindr). Grindr allows users to meet other men within close proximity using the mobile device's global positioning system (GPS) location-based services to show men nearby who are also on Grindr. The increases in P&S syphilis have been attributed in part to "HIV prevention fatigue", -- that is, diminished motivation to practice safer sex.

However, the news report above fails to characterize the cases of syphilis or gonococcal disease in Lane County, Oregon as to age, sex, sex behavior, or use of drugs, social networking Internet sites, and smartphone apps. A more detailed description of the cases would be appreciated.

For a discussion of gonococcal disease, please see moderator ML's comments in prior ProMED-mail posts Gonococcal disease - UK: increased cases, antibiotic resistance 20130301.1565249 and Gonococcal disease - USA: (ME) increased incidence 20121208.1443412. - Mod.ML]
